The scatter plot matrix and correlation matrix for Model I shows that the length of stay (Y) has low correlation to Age(X1) and Available facilities and services(X3) but moderate correlation to Infection Risk(X2). Overall, the predictor variables are not strongly correlated to each other.

The scatter plot matrix and correlation matrix for Model II shows that the length of stay (Y) has low correlation to No.if beds(X1) and Available facilities and services(X3) but moderate correlation to Infection Risk(X2). However, the predictor variable No.of beds (X1) is highly correlated to Available facilities and services (X3). This implys that Model II exhibits multicollinearity and the redundant predictor variable should be dropped from the model.

  1. For each of the two proposed models, fit first-order regression model
# Model 1
M1_Y = random_sample_data$`Length of stay`
M1_X1 = random_sample_data$Age
M1_X2 = random_sample_data$`Infection risk`
M1_X3 = random_sample_data$`Available facilities and services`

M1_data = data.frame(M1_Y, M1_X1, M1_X2, M1_X3)

M1 = lm(M1_Y ~ M1_X1 + M1_X2 + M1_X3, M1_data) # Model I
M1_coef = coef(M1)

  2. Using the F* test statistic, test whether or not the variable determined to be the best in part (b) is helpful in the regression model when X1 and X2 are included in the model; use \(\alpha\) = .05. State the alternatives, decision rule, and conclusion.

n = nrow(senic)
p = 2
alpha = .05

F_test_statistic = (anova(dataset2_model)[[2]][[3]] / 1) / (anova(dataset2_model)[[2]][[4]] / (n-4) ) 
F_test_statistic
## [1] 17.1871
F_distribution = qf(1-alpha, p-1, n-p)
F_distribution
## [1] 3.926607
if(F_test_statistic <= F_distribution){
 print("conclude H0")
}else{
 print("conclude Ha")
}
## [1] "conclude Ha"

Full model: \(Y_{i} = \beta_{0} + \beta_{1}X_{i1} + \beta_{2}X_{i2} + \beta_{4}X_{i4} + \epsilon_{i}\)
\(H_{0}: \beta_{4} = 0,\)
\(H_{a}: \beta_{4} \neq 0\)
\(SSR(X_{4} | X_{1}, X_{2}) =\) 37.8986373,
\(SSE(X_{1}, X_{2}, X_{4}) =\) 240.3517914

\(F* = \frac{SSR(X_{4} | X_{1}, X_{2})}{1} \frac{SSE(X_{1}, X_{2}, X_{4})}{n-4}\) = 17.19

\(F(.95, 1, 109) =\) 3.93

Decision rule:
If \(F* \leq\) 3.93 conclude \(H_{0},\)
otherwise conclude \(H_{a}\)

Conclusion:
Since \(F^* =\) 17.2 \(>\) 3.927, we conclude \(H_{a}\). The predictor variable \(X_{4}\) should not be dropped from the model that already contains \(X_{1}\) and \(X_{2}\).
